The Commissioner for health in Katsina state, Engr. Nuhu Yakubu, has denied report of confirmed case of Lassa fever in the state. He stated this on Friday while briefing pressmen at the state’s primary healthcare agency, said government has taken proactive steps for any eventuality that may occurred, by procuring modern health facilities against the outbreak. The commissioner has however hinted that five persons were actually suspected with the virus, after being diagnosed in Lagos were certified to be negative and only have ordinary fever. He stated that the state government had put health officials on red alert in the event of any suspected case, stressing that health officials would maintain a high index of suspicion for Lassa fever and treat all cases of fever symptoms with caution. The Commissioner, described Lassa fever as an endemic acute viral hemorrhage illness usually transmitted from rodents to human through ingestion of food or materials contaminated by excreta or urine of infected rodents. He added, “The disease is also transmitted from human to human, through direct contact with blood tissues, secretions and excretion of infected humans.’’ Yakubu allayed the fear of residents and advised them to avoid contact with rodents and ensure personal, as well as environmental hygiene. End